<worksheet label="ws-act-8-5-2">
  <activity xml:id="act-8-5-2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
      In <xref ref="act-8-5-1">Activity</xref>
      we determined small order Taylor polynomials for a few familiar functions,
      and also found general patterns in the derivatives evaluated at <m>0</m>.
      Use that information to write the Taylor series centered at <m>0</m> for the following functions.
    </p>
      <p/>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8-5-2-task-0">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{1-x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
            Small hints for each of the prompts above.
          </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>
            P(x) = 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + \cdots + x^n + \cdots
            </m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
            For <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{1-x}</m>, its Taylor series is
            <me>
              P(x) = 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + \cdots + x^n + \cdots
            </me></p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8-5-2-task-1">
      <statement>
        <p><m>f(x) = \cos(x)</m> (You will need to carefully consider how to indicate that many of the coefficients are 0.
            Think about a general way to represent an even integer.)
          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer>
        <p><m>
            P(x) = 1 - \frac{1}{2!}x^2 + \frac{1}{4!}x^4 - \cdots + (-1)^{n}\frac{1}{(2n)!}x^{2n} + \cdots 
            </m>.
          </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
            For <m>f(x) = \cos(x)</m>, its Taylor series is
            <me>
              P(x) = 1 - \frac{1}{2!}x^2 + \frac{1}{4!}x^4 - \cdots + (-1)^{n}\frac{1}{(2n)!}x^{2n} + \cdots
            </me>.
          </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8-5-2-task-2">
      <statement>
        <p><m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m> (You will need to carefully consider how to indicate that many of the coefficients are <m>0</m>.
            Think about a general way to represent an odd integer.)
          </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer>
        <p><m>
            P(x) = x - \frac{1}{3!}x^3 + \frac{1}{5!}x^5 - \cdots + (-1)^{n}\frac{1}{(2n+1)!}x^{2n+1} + \cdots 
            </m>.
          </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
            For <m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m>, its Taylor series is
            <me>
              P(x) = x - \frac{1}{3!}x^3 + \frac{1}{5!}x^5 - \cdots + (-1)^{n}\frac{1}{(2n+1)!}x^{2n+1} + \cdots
            </me>.
          </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8-5-2-task-3">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{1+x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>
            P_n(x) = 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + \cdots + x^n
            </m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
            For <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{1-x}</m>,
            <me>
              P_n(x) = 1 + x + x^2 + x^3 + \cdots + x^n
            </me></p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </activity>
</worksheet>
